ve through their worlds. Ultimately, Taylor demonstrates that theorizing value aids us in moving beyond the music itself toward understanding how musicians, workers in the music business, and audiences struggle to make and maintain what they value.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aMusicxEconomic aspects2DLC. 0aMusicxEconomic aspects. 0aMusicxLabor productivityxHistory2DLC. 0aMusicxLabor productivityxHistory. 0aMusicxSocial aspects2DLC. 0aMusicxSocial aspects. 0aValue2DLC. 0aValue. 7aMUSIC / Ethnomusicology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311135689140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478059349?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478059349423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478059349/original  a978-3-11-135689-1  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles